\begin{abstract}
% FIX
%Do parties target individuals or groups? This is a fundamental question to understand clientelism, and yet the literature does not offer a consensus. This paper argues that brokers target high-dense poverty clusters when political competition is high, and low-dense poverty clusters when political competition is low. Since heavy contestation requires more votes, motivated brokers have the incentives to engage in group-monitoring. Given that brokers cannot increase their monitoring capacities to target large groups, they take their risks and rely on the economies of scale and spillover effects that large aggregations of poor individuals provide. On the contrary, when political contestation is low, brokers target low-dense poverty clusters. This way of targeting is closer to a much secure investment. Building on recent research that gives emphasis to macro variables (group size and electoral competition), it also considers the issue of individual income. However, the paper departs from recent research in that the theory and models presented here do find that clientelism also happens to non-poor individuals only under low-competition settings. In non-contested districts, it is easier to deviate more resources to engage in rather expensive forms of vote-buying. Using Brazil as a case, the paper exploits the variations of personal incomes within different poverty-density contexts to support the theory. 
\end{abstract}

