% OK groups vs individuals: hook 1
There is no agreement on when parties target individuals and when parties should target groups. The distributive politics and vote-buying literatures have traditionally followed two different practices. Unfortunately, this decision seems to be grounded on foundations of research design than theoretical reasons. Consequently, it has been implied that the two strategies are interchangeable. On the one hand, the distributive politics literature has mostly focused on groups, usually districts or provinces (\citet[]{Dixit1996}, \citet[]{Khemani2015}, \citet[]{Calvo2004}). In this literature, incumbent parties deliver public-sector jobs or construction projects contingent on the support of \emph{groups} of individuals. On the other hand, the vote-buying literature has typically focused on individuals and their characteristics such as socio-economic or electoral profiles (\citet[]{Carlin2015}). 

% OK income: hook 2
The most consolidated agreement is on the positive effects of poverty on vote-buying (\citet[]{Calvo2004,Weitz-shapiro})\footnote{Vote-buying is ``the proffering to voters of cash or (more commonly) minor consumption goods by political parties, in office or in opposition, in exchange for the recipient's vote'' (\citet[p. 67]{Brusco2004}). In the rest of this note, we use clientelism and vote-buying interchangeable.}. \citet{Kitschelt2000}\footnote{See also Kitschelt and Altamirano in \citet[ch. 10]{Carlin:2015}.}, For example, \citet{Brusco2004}, \citet[]{Stokes:2013cj} and \citet[]{Nazareno2008a} explain that since the poor derive more utility from immediate transfers than future and risky returns associated to policy packages, clientelistic political parties target the poor \emph{only}. This canonical predictor has been recently challenged, however. \citet{Szwarcberg2013} ``challenges the assumption [brokers] with access to material benefits will always distribute goods to low-income voters in exchange for electoral support'', while \citet{GonzalezOcantos:2012vr} and \citet[]{Holland2015} explain that income (measured at the individual level) has little or no effect on vote-buying. Why do newer scholarly work report null fundings on poverty, the \emph{most} important predictor of vote-buying? 

% OK questions
The lack of clarity on whether parties should target groups or/and individuals and when (if) they should switch or combine strategies, leave us in big confusion. \citet[]{Zarazaga2015a} argues that brokers do not offer a uniform reward to all voters. We generalize this idea and argue that depending on the incentive structure, brokers target groups or individuals. Part of this incentive is shaped by individual wealth. However, an important gap in the literature is that it is not explicit on whether ``the poor'' constitute poor \emph{groups} or poor \emph{individuals} (or both). There has not been an explicit effort to theorize about the different set of incentives these two targeting strategies present to both parties and individuals (either considered on their own or nested in groups). For example, \citet[10]{Kitschelt2007} argue that political parties target ``individuals \emph{or} identifiable small groups''\footnote{Emphasis added.}. However, it is not clear what makes parties to focus on one or the other, or both at the same time, why and how. This paper tries to shed light on those issues.

% OK ARGUMENT and // Summary of the paper: LIT REVIEW // METHODS (0)
We argue that the decision brokers face on whether to target groups or individuals is context specific. The paper systematizes this decision by arguing that the outcome is a function of three factors, i.e. individuals' income level, whether individuals are nested within poor or non-poor contexts, and the level of political competition. Given the nesting structure of the argument and the empirics, we are able to provide interesting predictions such as the decomposing the different effects on clientelism of ``being poor'' and ``living in a poor area''. To the best of our knowledge, this is the first time such comparison is made. Four ideal types are presented, poor individuals nested in (1) poor and (2) non-poor clusters, and non-poor individuals nested in (3) poor and (4) non-poor contexts. In addition to that, depending on how challenged the incumbent party is, brokers take advantage of the different economic incentives each combination has, deploying either individual or group-targeting strategies for each. 

%  OK ARGUMENT and // Summary of the paper: LIT REVIEW // METHODS (1)
Each combination presents different incentives for both brokers and individuals that make them engage in clientelism, either delivering it or accepting it. The argument has three constitutive parts. First, when individuals are highly identifiable, such as when the poor are nested within non-poor areas or when the non-poor are nested within poor areas, brokers will be in a better position to keep those individuals more accountable. Second, when political competition is low there are less incentives to spend too much resources on clientelism, if at all. For example, even when non-poor individuals nested in poor contexts are more identifiable, under low electoral pressures, clientelism is very low. Third, low personal incomes are neither a sufficient nor a necessary condition for clientelism. Though higher individual incomes discount faster immediate clientelistic transfers, \emph{in general but not always} poor individuals have more probabilities of receiving it. One of the important propositions of the argument is that clientelism is not channeled to individuals only because of their personal incomes. In fact, non-poor individuals (under certain conditions) receive clientelism too. Consequently, we depart from the canonical (and until recently) (un)challenged finding that only ``the'' poor receive clientelism. 


