The four ideal situations in these three contexts are exemplified in \autoref{tab:strategy:set}. Brokers will engage in \emph{individual targeting} in quadrants 1 and 4. As part of what is gained securing each vote is spent in making sure that happens, individual targeting represents a safer investments though its returns are much more limited. Quadrant 1 has higher clientelism than quadrant 4 as poor have higher marginal returns for the same dollar spent in clientelism compared to the non-poor people in quadrant 4. Quadrant 3 represents a situation when politicians are in high need of more electoral support, and when the size of the poor is large, they engage in group-monitoring. Rather than securing each vote individually, brokers take advantage of the spillover effects of clientelism. Finally, quadrant 2 represents a situation where non-poor individuals nested in non-poor areas have a some probability of receiving clientelism. Here brokers engage in group targeting. We theorize that in contexts where there exists less political competition, there also exists less checks and balances too. Even when politicians are not in need of more electoral support, they engage in this expensive form of clientelism which might be understood as embezzlement.


% This paper proceeds as follows
This paper proceeds as follows. First, it reviews classic and newer research on vote buying, particularly paying attention to explanations that, though vaguely, touch upon the distinction between individual and group targeting. We emphasize on the main tensions regarding the lack of clarity on whether which strategy is the most efficient, when and why. Second, it presents the details of the argument. Third, the paper presents the methodology. Exploiting within-municipality variations of individual income in both low and high density contexts in Brazil, and a matched design, the empirical section tests and presents supporting evidence for each of the ideal types. Fourth, the paper offers some final considerations.


\section*{When do parties target individuals and when groups?} 

% OK new papers // PRESENT MAIN THEORIES // (-0)
In both the classic and the newer literatures coexist theories, methodologies, measurement and identification strategies that either focus on only individual \emph{or} group targeting, assuming that both strategies are interchangeable. In fact, most of the times, the distinction is rather product of the method or epistemological tradition. For example, most ethnographers have considered individual targeting (see for example \citet{Scott1972}, \citet{Auyero2000} and \citet{Szwarcberg2013}). While papers employing experimental methods tend to vary, but most accounts focus on individuals aggregated at some level (see for example \citet{Weitz-shapiro} and \citet{Gonzalez-Ocantos2012}). Rather than describing a detailed list of works and their methodologies, the important point is that what has driven the decision to study group-based and/or individual-based targeting strategies (by separate or jointly, as this paper does) has been mostly driven by considerations of research design. Unfortunately, there is no clear theory for why, how and when parties would engage in one or the other. In addition to that, this interchangeability also \emph{implies} that there is no difference between these strategies. As this paper suggests, the structure of incentives each of them provides is something that the literature should address.

% OK new papers // PRESENT MAIN THEORIES - bajada //
The lack of theoretical discussion on whether parties target groups and/or individuals, and when, has produced a tension in the vote-buying literature. This tension is more noticeable when we consider how three standard \emph{contextual} predictors of clientelism (population size, associationism  and political competition) interplay differently when we make the explicit distinction between \emph{individual} and \emph{group} poverty.


% // size (1.1)
\subsection*{Population Size and Coordination Dilemmas}
One of the classic contextual factors has been the size of the community. Group-size has always been an important consideration in social science. Classic political economy literature has longly argued how large groups face more coordination dilemmas (see for example \citet[]{Aldrich}). The main intuition is that if a individual's vote is bought, she may be tempted to accept the benefit and then vote for her preferred candidate. In cases where the size of the community is large, she will hope others will vote for the candidate so the broker continues delivering benefits. Taking this idea as a starting point, several scholars have argued that smaller groups are preferred for brokers because they defect less. For example, \citet[323]{Stokes2005}, \citet[10]{Kitschelt2007} and \citet[p. 67]{Magaloni:2008bq} suggest that the size of population is negatively associated to clientelism. Smaller communities should have higher likelihoods of receiving clientelistic goods since they are easier to monitor. This mechanism, with some modifications, has been readdressed very recently. For the Colombian case, \citet{Rueda2016} argues that clientelism is higher in situations where the electoral results of small groups are available. In Nigeria, for example, \citet[]{Bratton2008a} finds that the strongest predictor of defection is the expectation of others defecting (which is a function of size too). In Brazil too, \citet[p. 456]{Gingerich2013} find that ``vote brokerage thrives in municipalities with very small electorates''. 


% // CRITICIZE size (1.2)
Parties systematically target small-sized communities. Though implied that the literature is referring to individual targeting, it is not clear how political parties derive enough electoral revenues from such a strategy. \citet[]{Brusco2004} and \citet[]{Stokes2005} argue that brokers develop very good skills that even allow them to infer whether individual clients in small-sized communities voted for the party by \emph{looking at them in the eyes}. For the Brazilian case, similar evidence is suggested in \citet{Gay1999,Gay1998}. This strategy implies that local brokers monitor, target, enforce and mobilize electoral support in a one-to-one basis. The theoretical challenge is that this method seems to be extremely expensive given the handful of votes brokers can individually secure. Hence the costs increase linearly with the size of the targeted population, even in low-density population contexts. The broker's production-possibility frontier cannot be shifted upwards either. Monitoring capacities are bounded. Simply put, at some point party machines simply run out of brokers. However, when we distinguish between group-based and individual targeting strategies, brokers can still monitor individuals with some degree of precision in small communities. The important question, however, is what parties do when they face large communities. Do they just stop being clientelistic? Under certain conditions, coordination among individuals nested in very large sized groups is still \emph{very} possible (see \citet{Olson:1965wz}). Hence, this begs the question of \emph{when} and \emph{why} would clientelistic political parties would engage in this costly strategy. And the question for the complementary strategy is still unanswered: Is this strategy exclusive? Does individual targeting in lowly populated areas \emph{prevent} clientelistic political parties targeting highly populated areas? The argument presented here does not argue against this particular strategy. Rather than that, it builds on that idea but explains how and why this strategy is just part of a larger set of strategies. Particularly, this paper presents an argument where parties make use of simultaneous segmented targeting techniques. As the {\color{red} argument section presents}, parties do engage in individual targeting but they rather fix their spendings based on the size of the poor group, individual's personal incomes and the degree in which the incumbent party is electorally contested.

\subsection*{Civic Associations and Organization Buying}

% OK new papers // PRESENT MAIN THEORIES // size and networks (2)
Another important contextual explanatory factor is whether individuals are involved in certain social networks. According to the literature, civic associations might help solving a big portion of the challenges large-sized groups present to brokers. In low-information environments most brokers cannot observe individual electoral behavior. As argued above, brokers might resort to different strategies instead of just stop being clientelistic. Given this impossibility to observe individual's behavior, brokers employ substitutes that allow them to make safer inferences, even in large-sized group contexts, for example by outsourcing monitoring and enforcing to formal and/or informal \emph{networks}. \citet{Schaffer2015} explains that clientelism is ``socially multiplied'', as party machines target individuals ``who are opinion-leading epicenters'' in informal situations. If parties buy turnout (\citet[]{Nichter2008}), they will most probably target associations too, as ``citizens immersed in clientelistic networks [...] have a higher probability of voting than the rest'' (\citet[p. 7]{Carreras2013}). In a similar vein, \citet{Calvo2012} argue that parties target formal ``partisan networks'', in what has been called ``organization buying'' (\citet[p. 250-251]{Stokes:2013cj}). For example, \citet[p. 16]{Holland2015} explains that when ``parties lack their own brokerage networks [they seek] to capitalize on organizational networks instead''. As \citet[]{Rueda2014a} also explains, parties tend to target very specific civic associations\footnote{Particularly, associations of ``seniors and associations of single mothers, organizing trips to recreational centers outside the city where all their expenses are covered'' (p. 13).}. Paradoxically, the stronger the civic society, i.e. the more organized it is, the more clientelism.

% criticize network approach
The positive relationship between group-membership and clientelism is intuitive and appealing. However, what has not been explored yet is whether clientelism is explained by the ``nesting'' or the ``organization buying''  components attached group-membership. Membership into local grass-root associations typically also involve a situation where (typically) poor individuals are nested in contexts of high-poor density. Keeping coordination costs constant, groups typically are formed to address collective problems that otherwise would be much costly to solve by individuals on their own. If that were the case, formal group \emph{membership} should be spuriously related to clientelism. Is clientelism associated to group membership \emph{itself}, or is it associated to the density of the poor that is also present in associations? This paper supports the intuition that there is a positive relationship on clientelism. However, given the identification strategy employed in this paper, we are able to separate the effects of being involved at the local level at different poverty-density nesting levels. Though local involvement does have a positive effect on clientelism, the larger the density of the poor, the higher probability of being targeted. 

\subsection*{Political Competition}
% PRESENT HERE THE political competition ISSUE
In an important paper, \citet[]{Weitz-shapiro} argues that higher levels of political competition in the presence of low socioeconomic levels at the municipal level are positively associated to clientelism in several Argentine municipalities. In the absence of these two, politicians opt-out of clientelism to avoid audience costs. We adopt the same empirical strategy and measure poverty and political competition at the municipal level. Building on that intuition, this paper incorporates individual socio-economic levels and  conceptualize (and empirically model) how different combinations of these three factors change broker's cost/benefit rationale. However, it departs from \citet[]{Weitz-shapiro} in that we exploit the idea of ``costs'' more explicit. In \citet[]{Weitz-shapiro}'s argument, losses are conceptualized in terms of ``moral costs''\footnote{\citet[]{Weitz-shapiro} argues that politicians opt-out of clientelism since non-poor individuals are more likely to condemn clientelism ``due to self-interest or because of \emph{moral} concern[s]'' (emphasis is mine). Self-interest refers to the idea that what is distributed through clientelism is discounted from the pool of resources theoretically available to be spent on policy packages. That \emph{is} an economic cost. Certainly building on that intuition, we incorporate the economic advantages/costs of targeting individuals \emph{or} groups, and when those strategies are efficient and when they are not.}. These type of costs have been theorized in the literature very recently. For example, \citet{Carlin2015} argues that citizens endowed with more democratic values feel more``moral repugnance'' about clientelism. Similarly, \citet{Vicente2014} argues that vote-buying practices have an ``immoral/illegal connotation''. Since clientelism is loaded with unethical associations, \citet{Gonzalez-Ocantos2012} find that individuals usually do not elicit truthful answers when directly asked about clientelism to avoid social stigma. However, it is not clear how individuals who benefit from clientelism really \emph{understand} how this practice harms democracy. Citizens endowed with more democratic values systematically have  higher incomes and better education. In fact \citet{GonzalezOcantos2014} find that while the concrete benefits obtained through clientelism are in general well understood, ``the abstract societal costs of such exchanges are often distant from the every-day world in which clientelistic relationships are formed''. According to their experimental evidence, more educated individuals condemn more, individuals with more exposure to it along with the poor condemn less. 

% concluding paragraph, % purpose of this paper: 
We are left with many questions. There is no consensus on how individual characteristics such as income and macro-structural factors such as the size of the population, the size of the poor group and different levels political competition \emph{interplay together} helping/harming clientelism. It is not clear how both levels of aggregations \emph{shape} broker's incentives to opt for clientelism.  We share \citet{Carlin2015}'s diagnosis, in that ``[e]xisting research looks almost exclusively at individuals' socio-economic and, specially, electoral profile [and] [y]et our knowledge of who parties target remains incomplete''. Hence, more than being an issue about the unit of analyses, we argue that there are very different consequences and explanations for why parties might want to engage in individual or group-based targeting strategies. 


