\section*{Argument}
 
% Intro
Generalizing the idea that the poor have higher discount rates, we argue that the effects of ``being poor'' and ``living in a poor area'' posit different types of incentives depending on how electorally challenged politicians are. Depending on the incentive structure, brokers are expected to target groups or individuals. These distinctions are novel and improve our understanding of clientelism. In our argument, when certain conditions are met, non-poor individuals do receive clientelism. This might explain why some newer research has not found evidence in support of the most widely accepted predictor in the literature. In addition to that, our research design allow us to observe how both individual income and the density of the poor contribute in different ways to the model.

\subsection*{Individual Targeting}

%% identifiable
Brokers will have incentives to engage in individual targeting when targets are easily \emph{identifiable}. Identifiability helps brokers to keep targeted individuals electorally accountable. Higher levels of identification also reduce the costs of keeping the clientelistic contract enforceable. Whereas individual targeting is the safest bet a broker can make, this mechanism is more expensive as it requires brokers having close relationships with  clients. Party machines know that more resources will need to be allocated to finance dedicated individual targeting for specific individuals. Personalized individual targeting supposes brokers with good-quality local information. Scholars generally agree that the source of information are social networks. For example, \citet[p. 15]{Carlin2015} argues that ``[u]nquestionably, brokers are deeply nested in social networks'', while \citet[p. 864]{Inan2012a} argues that  brokers ``hire respected community leaders in each village to interact with voters to promote their candidacy and offer them money [..] in exchange for the promise of their vote''. Building on this idea, our argument supposes brokers with local knowledge too. However, this knowledge comes from the individual's notoriety rather than his/her ties with local groups. Our identification strategy allows us to investigate this mechanism.


%% political competition
When political competition is low, politicians will have incentives to target identifiable poor individuals nested in low-poor density contexts (quadrant 1 in \autoref{tab:strategy:set}), but when political competition is high, brokers will have incentives to target identifiable non-poor individuals nested in high-poor density contexts (quadrant 4 in \autoref{tab:strategy:set}). As argued before, individual targeting is expensive. Hence, brokers resort to this strategy only when it is necessary. Low political contestation implies a situation where there is no need to invest too much in clientelism. Given that poor individuals have higher discount rates and they are cheaper to buy, they are ideal targets in this context: poor individuals with higher discount rates who are highly identifiable. However, when politicians are heavily contested, brokers have no other choice than spend more resources on clientelism to keep the party in office. \emph{Besides} targeting quadrant 1, they also target identifiable non-poor individuals nested in poor contexts in quadrant 4. Though these clients they are more expensive to buy, engaging in this strategy justifiable to stay the office. Brokers want to stay in quadrant 1, but have no choice than going to quadrant 4 when political competition is high. This paper then generalizes the argument in \citet{Weitz-shapiro}. In this particular context, when political competition is low, party machines do not stop being clientelistic, but engage in individual targeting aiming identifiable individuals with larger discount rates (i.e., poor individuals).

\subsection*{Group Targeting}

% Group Targeting: waiting // introducing potential beneficiaries
Brokers will have incentives to target groups even when individual targets are not identifiable, \emph{if} the socio-economic level of the group provides \emph{spillover} effects. This portion of the argument considers that individuals who are inserted in targeted groups still vote for the broker's party even when they have not received the benefit. For example, \citet[]{Rueda2014a} proposes a formal model which suggests that vote buying is facilitated when voters care about the welfare of other voters. While \citet[p. 65]{Auyero:2000ta} explains the case of \emph{Alfonsina} in Argentina. \emph{Alfonsina} was part of the \emph{broker's inner circle} and got a job as a cleaning lady in a public school. As the broker explained to her before getting the job, \emph{Alfonsina} had to be \emph{patient} because as a member of the circle, she was in the pool of potential beneficiaries. It was only a ``matter of time'' so she could get the job. Building on this intuition, our model presents two ideal types, \emph{actual} and \emph{potential} beneficiaries. The former receive particularistic benefits ``today'' and vote for the broker's candidate ``tomorrow'', while the latter do not receive benefits today (in the expectation of receiving them in the future) but \emph{still} vote for the broker's candidate ``tomorrow''.

% Group Targeting: potential beneficiaries // explanation - expansion
In part, group targeting is possible because potential beneficiaries still vote for the broker's candidate without the benefit (in the hope of being benefited in the short run). Potential beneficiaries have two possible strategies. First, they could defect and vote for another candidate, who might or might not bring them benefits. Second, potential beneficiaries could continue voting for the known broker and wait. Individual income also plays a role. Given that the poor are risk-averse, potential beneficiaries are better-off waiting (and voting for the current broker's party) than defecting. In a slightly different research project, \citet[p. 20]{Magaloni:2008bq} explains that under non-democratic contexts, voters have incentives to keep voting for the incumbent government, \emph{even when they oppose it}. The Mexican PRI lasted so long not because of electoral fraud but because voters supported what it represented the ``known devil''. As she explains, hegemonic parties survive when they are able to sustain long-term economic growth and a constant supply of clientelistic transfers. As of vote-buying, \citet[p. 14]{Zarazaga2014} explains that ``[b]rokers and voters' interests are aligned. The flow of resources to voters is dependent on their brokers' electoral success. If the broker loses the election and is replaced, clients do not know what the new broker will offer them. A new broker may access fewer resources or choose to distribute them to other people; brokers often remind voters about this''. Building on these ideas, we argue that the transaction cost of switching brokers or defecting is very costly since it also involves building confidence relationships with the new broker from scratch. Reputation costs also keep targeted individuals disciplined. Having defected with the former broker once, makes the voter a defection-prone type one, increasing even more the cost of building those relationships. 

% quadrant 3 and 2
When political competition is high, brokers will be in need of securing more electoral support at the lowest price. The cheapest source of electoral support lives in the intersection of low income individuals masked in areas where the density of the poor is high. However, under these circumstances brokers cannot incur in the extremely high costs of engaging in individual targeting. Since individuals are masked within their environments, in these cases identifiability is difficult to get. Rather than that, brokers have economic incentives to target these groups of poor individuals but rely on the spillovers these type of groups provide. For the reasons explained above, when brokers invest in group targeting, the electoral benefits for the broker get multiplied. What is invested in \emph{actual} beneficiaries also makes \emph{potential} beneficiaries to vote for the broker's party. Quadrant 3 in \autoref{tab:strategy:set} depicts such settings. In low-information environments, brokers take advantage of self-enforced compliance mechanisms. Turning into quadrant 2, non-poor individuals nested in non-poor groups are also difficult to identify. However, given that non-poor individuals give less value to the same dollar invested in clientelism than poor individuals, brokers will target these groups only when brokers have less electoral pressures (low political competition). In this setting, elected members have more room to move, and hence embezzlement (as a way of expensive clientelism) is more likely. In these cases, clientelism has the lowest levels.

