\section*{Case Selection, Data and Design}

% explain the identification strategy, introducing Brazil as the case
The unit of analysis is individuals. Particularly, we are interested in testing the effects of individuals with different income levels being nested in communities with different poverty sizes at different levels of political competition on receiving clientelism. We find Brazil to be a good case, and so we use survey data from 2010 from \citet{LAPOP2010}\footnote{``I thank the Latin American Public Opinion Project (LAPOP) and its major supporters (the United States Agency for International Development, the United Nations Development Program, the Inter-American Development Bank, and Vanderbilt University) for making the data available''. The sample consists of five strata representing the five main geographical regions of Brazil. Each stratum was further sub-stratified by urban and rural areas.} to tests this idea. Brazil constitutes a good case as its poverty structure allows having poor individuals nested in non-poor areas (and vice versa). Simply put, low income levels do not properly classify individuals into high-poverty density contexts (and vice versa). To ensure this assumption holds, the data was preprocessed using a matching algorithm which is explained below. In this case, the advantage of this method is that, based on observables, the systematic relationship between income and the density of the poor is forced to be zero (\citet{King2011}). \autoref{fig:municipality:wealth:large:plot} in the Appendix shows that the raw dataset have already embedded into them low levels of correlation (\Sexpr{round(cor(dat$wagehalf, dat$wealth), 2)}), while the matched dataset have even lower levels (\Sexpr{round(cor(m.data$wagehalf, m.data$wealth), 2)}). 


