\subsection*{Density of the Poor, Political Competition and Income}

% Density of the Poor
To measure the size of the poor, we follow a similar strategy presented in \citet{Weitz-shapiro}, measuring the degree of poverty at the municipal level. Using information from the 2010 Brazilian census\footnote{Official data comes from the Bureau of Statistics of Brazil \href{http://www.ibge.gov.br}{IBGE}.}, a variable that measures the percentage of individuals who live with less than half of the minimum wage was constructed. Given that we observe the municipality of residence for each individual interviewed by LAPOP, we were able to triangulate that percentage for each individual. Although this percentage was originally a semi-continuous variable, it had to be dichotomized at the median to be able to construct the matched (\Sexpr{round(as.numeric(median(m.data$wagehalf)), 2)}\%). There have been theoretical advances regarding general treatment effects regimes for continuous or semi-continuous response doses (\citet{Ratkovic2012}, \citet{Hirano2004}), algorithms capable to match on continuous treatment variables are not common. \autoref{fig:tgraph:plot} shows the continuous distribution dichotomized at the median (dashed line). However, we still provide alternative models using the original continuous variable as a robustness, matching on the generalized propensity score. In these cases, the \texttt{GPS} is used as a weighting regressor not as a matching device (see \citet{Imbens2004}, \citet{Guardabascio2014} and \citet[]{Imai2014b}). The advantage of this strategy is that it does not require dichotomization. 


