% Matching
To break further systematic relationships between group poverty and other important confounding factors, the size of the community proxied by an urban/rural variable was also included in the matching procedure along with municipal opposition and individual involvement in civic associations. This strategy sought to break any systematic relationships between the size of the poor and these variables by balancing the distribution of these variables via a deleting procedure\footnote{The final procedure matched \Sexpr{as.numeric(as.data.frame(sum.match[2])[2,1])} individuals living in the low-density condition with \Sexpr{as.numeric(as.data.frame(sum.match[2])[2,2])} individuals living in the high-density condition.}. A good overall-balance\footnote{See \autoref{fig:balance:distance:plot} in the Appendix.} and covariate balance were obtained (see \autoref{fig:balance:plot}). From a statistical standpoint, preprocessed datasets are less model-dependent (\citet{Ho2006}) and prevent analysts making extreme counterfactuals (\citet{King2005a}). The matching routine used was the ``coarsen exact matching'' \texttt{CEM} which is a class of exact matching (\citet{King2015b})\footnote{``The basic idea of CEM is to coarsen each variable by recoding so that substantively indistinguishable values are grouped and assigned the same numerical value (groups may be the same size or different sizes depending on the substance of the problem). Then, the ``exact matching'' algorithm is applied to the coarsened data to determine the matches and to prune unmatched units. Finally, the coarsened data are discarded and the original (uncoarsened) values of the matched data are retained'' (\citet[p. 8]{Iacus2011}). ``Automated coarsening'' was used (\citet[p. 7]{Iacus2009a}).}. \autoref{tab:sum:stats:r} and \autoref{tab:sum:stats:m} provide summary statistics for both the matched and raw datasets {\color{red}PENDING}. Both the preprocessed and raw datasets have \Sexpr{length(levels(m.data$municipality))} municipalities. \autoref{fig:municipality:income:large:plot:matched} shows the municipalities and which ones are considered as ``high'' or ``low'' in terms of the density of the poor. The figure also shows that there exists  considerable variance regarding income in both high and low poverty density conditions\footnote{\autoref{municipality:sample:plot} shows the distribution of observations by municipalities, by income levels in both raw and matches datasets.}.

