# Effectiveness Gap

  ## ``Latin American countries exhibit a striking ``effectiveness gap'' in that politicians make great efforts to target voters with clientelistic goods, but fail to generate a commensurate number of votes with these practices'' (p. 247).
  ## ``The dominant argument about the incidence of clientelism in partisan politics has to do with economic development. Poor people laboring at the bare subsistence threshold are expected to discount the future and prefer an immediate, tangible personal direct gain of clientelistic inducement compared to a distance, less tangible collective indirect policy gain. Conversely, as citizen's income rises, the material inducements of clientelism become of questionable value'' (p. 254).
  	### This is an explanation about ``clientelistic effort''. What if ``the density of the poor'' decreases the amount of effort needed to be clientelism an effective strategy? This should also be mediated by the degree of competition.
